snippet.textDisplay: You had me scrambling with Travolta...(I'm getting too old for this) Light House RULES. I saw Richard Jewell today, and performance wise, Paul Walter Hauser is marvelous. You remember him in I Tanya, where he stole every scene he was in, and that film could easily have been best picture. But Light House...I cheered. I saw the preview for it in an Imax theater, and that damn box was so big...bigger than what we get it repertory theaters like our Castro theater in S.F., with it's giant box of a screen set up for all the 1930's classics. That knocked me out, before I could finally see it in a standard theater. The film excited me the way Kubrick's films did before 2001. (I refuse to compare 2001 to anything). All right, five minutes to midnight, New Years Eve.  I need something to give me heartburn... by the way, I got myself The Brothers Quay Collection for Christmas....

Happy New Year Chris!!!
A few seconds ago I just cleared my "Watch History" and "Search History", so this is the first video I am watching in 2020!!!
Great list man, hope nobody gets too pissed that movies like "Avengers:Endgame" and "Joker" were merely "Honorable Mentions". I have to admit, I haven't heard of a majority of these movies, while I have heard of movies like "The Lighthouse", "Doctor Sleep", "Jo Jo Rabbit", and "Marriage Story", but movies like "Shadow", "The Nightingale", and "Portrait of a Lady on Fire" have utterly eluded me. I'm gonna need to check some of those out sometime this year.
Looking forward to what you have in store for 2020! :)

snippet.textDisplay:
Best movie of 2019 for me JOKER 🃏

I feel like in terms of comic book mentality/vibes, Ledger did an excellent portrayal of the goofy, dark, and colorful villain.

However, I believe Phoenix in certain ways did better in portraying Joker that wasn’t there with Ledger. Like, from beginning to end, you’re on his side. When you see all the shit he endures throughout, you feel very sympathetic for him. I can’t remember a time where in a movie I felt extremely sorry for a villain, or just a character in general. Phoenix made the character seem relatable and as someone who constantly gets chewed up and spit out in society and no one gives a damn to the point where he just loses his mind. It didn’t feel like I was watching a comic book movie/very fictitious Summer blockbuster, it felt like I was watching pure art unfold before my eyes. Demonstrating the chaos that ensues when we tend to mess with the wrong person/people.
